{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599392"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:53:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:53:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15547"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15547"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.86,0.1,0.05,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8238"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70196"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8238"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55660"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5103"},{"type":"tags","id":"10113"},{"type":"tags","id":"10123"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19920"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70196"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis is essential for regulating metabolism and development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following represents the correct sequence of hormone release in the thyroid axis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyrotropin-releasing hormone \u2192 Thyroid-stimulating hormone \u2192 Triiodothyronine and thyroxine","Thyroid-stimulating hormone \u2192 Thyrotropin-releasing hormone \u2192 Triiodothyronine and thyroxine","Triiodothyronine and thyroxine \u2192 Thyroid-stimulating hormone \u2192 Thyrotropin-releasing hormone","Triiodothyronine and thyroxine \u2192 Thyrotropin-releasing hormone \u2192 Thyroid-stimulating hormone","Thyroid-stimulating hormone \u2192 Triiodothyronine and thyroxine \u2192 Thyrotropin-releasing hormone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHormone release in the thyroid axis begins with \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyrotropin-releasing hormone (TRH)\u003C/strong\u003E from the hypothalamus, which stimulates the anterior pituitary to release \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH)\u003C/strong\u003E. TSH then acts on the thyroid gland to produce and release \u003Cstrong\u003Etriiodothyronine (T3) and thyroxine (T4)\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sequence cannot begin with \u003Cstrong\u003ETSH\u003C/strong\u003E as it requires TRH stimulation. \u003Cstrong\u003ET3 and T4\u003C/strong\u003E are end-products of this cascade and cannot initiate the sequence. The thyroid hormones provide negative feedback to both the hypothalamus and anterior pituitary to regulate their production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis follows the sequence: TRH (hypothalamus) \u2192 TSH (anterior pituitary) \u2192 T3 \u0026 T4 (thyroid gland)","Negative feedback by T3 \u0026 T4 inhibits both TRH and TSH release"],"references":["Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55660"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15547"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55660"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T08:32:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T08:33:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8238"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70196"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"g